Differential equations in Maple¶

A guest lecture by Robert M. Corless¶

Editor-in-Chief, Maple Transactions

We have a "Student Paper" column, and submissions from students are welcome.

Home page

Maple has several features for solving differential equations. SymPy in Python has many very similar features, so learning Maple's features will help you to understand SymPy's (which are weaker, but don't cost money).

Let's begin with the simplest differential equation of all:

\begin{equation} y' = f(x) \end{equation}
In [1]:
dsolve( diff(y(x),x) = f(x), y(x) );

kilobytes used=1799, alloc=5424, time=0.25
Out[1]:
$$y \left(x \right) = \int f \left(x \right)d x +c_{1}$$
In [2]:
dsolve( diff( y(x), x ) = 1/(1+x), y(x) );
Out[2]:
$$y \left(x \right) = \ln \left(1+x \right)+c_{1}$$

Now let's add an initial condition:

In [3]:
dsolve( { diff(y(x),x)=sqrt(x), y(0)=3}, y(x) );
Out[3]:
$$y \left(x \right) = \frac{2 x^{\frac{3}{2}}}{3}+3$$

Notice the details of the syntax.

y(x) means "y" is a function of "x"

(Other variable names are possible: you could have y(t) being a function of t or u(v) where u is a function of v or whatever you want, almost.)

diff( y(x), x ) means the derivative of y with respect to x

{ } are "set brackets" so

{ diff(y(x),x)=sqrt(x), y(0)=3 }

is the set containing the differential equation and an initial condition.

Now let's try a harder equation.

In [4]:
dsolve( {diff(y(x),x) = mu*y(x), y(0)=C}, y(x) );

kilobytes used=5093, alloc=13872, time=0.78
Out[4]:
$$y \left(x \right) = C \,{\mathrm e}^{\mu x}$$

That is (of course) the exponential growth equation (if $\mu > 0$) (the Greek letters are just spelled out in Maple input). The constant C is the initial concentration/population.

In [5]:
Logistic := diff( y(t), t ) = mu*y(t)*( L - y(t) );
Out[5]:
$$\frac{d}{d t}y \left(t \right) = \mu y \left(t \right) \left(L -y \left(t \right)\right)$$
In [6]:
LogisticSolution := dsolve( {Logistic, y(0)=varepsilon}, y(t) );
Out[6]:
$$y \left(t \right) = \frac{L \varepsilon}{\left(-\varepsilon +L \right) {\mathrm e}^{-\mu L t}+\varepsilon}$$
In [7]:
limit( rhs(LogisticSolution), t=infinity ) assuming mu>0, L>0, varepsilon > 0;
Out[7]:
$$L$$

"Nondimensionalization" helps in symbolic computation, too.

In [8]:
step1 := PDETools:-dchange( {y(t)=L*Y(t)}, Logistic, {Y(t)});
Out[8]:
$$L \left(\frac{d}{d t}Y \left(t \right)\right) = \mu L Y \left(t \right) \left(L -L Y \left(t \right)\right)$$
In [9]:
step2 := normal( step1/L );
Out[9]:
$$\frac{d}{d t}Y \left(t \right) = -\mu Y \left(t \right) L \left(Y \left(t \right)-1\right)$$

I always forget which way the "change of variables" command wants the transformation written. Every code writer has their own logic, so one has to read the documentation or do trial-and-error. I am leaving my mistakes in this Jupyter Notebook so you can learn from them.

In [10]:
step3 := PDETools:-dchange( {tau=mu*L*t}, step2, {tau} );

Runtime error: Error, (in dchange/info) the new variables are not contained in the rhs of the direct transformation equations
In [11]:
step3 := PDETools:-dchange( {t=tau/(mu*L)}, step2, {tau} );
Out[11]:
$$\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial \tau}Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right)\right) \mu L = -\mu Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right) L \left(Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right)-1\right)$$
In [12]:
step4 := normal( step3/(L*mu) );
Out[12]:
$$\frac{\partial}{\partial \tau}Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right) = -Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right) \left(Y \left(\tau , L , \mu \right)-1\right)$$

Maple is correct but pedantic: $Y$ is a function of $\tau$ and also a function of those constants $L$ and $\mu$. But the derivatives are only with respect to $\tau$ so it's really an ordinary differential equation, not a partial differential equation.

In [13]:
step5 := eval( step4, Y(tau,L,mu) = Y(tau) ); # Remove clutter

                           dtau
Out[13]:
$$\frac{d}{d \tau}Y \left(\tau \right) = -Y \left(\tau \right) \left(Y \left(\tau \right)-1\right)$$
In [14]:
nondimensionalSolution := dsolve( {step5, Y(0)=s}, Y(tau) );
Out[14]:
$$Y \left(\tau \right) = -\frac{s}{\left(s -1\right) {\mathrm e}^{-\tau}-s}$$
In [15]:
limit( rhs(nondimensionalSolution), tau=infinity );
Out[15]:
$$1$$
In [16]:
eval( nondimensionalSolution, tau=0 );
Out[16]:
$$Y \left(0\right) = s$$

One reason to nondimensionalize is so we can plot things "all at once".

In [17]:
plot( [seq( eval( rhs(nondimensionalSolution), s=sigma), 
             sigma=[0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9, 1.1, 1.3, 1.5, 1.7, 1.9] )]
             , tau=0..5, labels=[mu*L*t, y/L], gridlines );
Out[17]:

Some limitations¶

Maple's "dsolve" command is very strong, but it can't solve every equation. Here's one where the best it can do is to "reduce the order". The output is very hard to read, too (it prints better in a Maple worksheet---the Jupyter Notebook interface is quite new and not all the wilder things look good in it yet).

In [18]:
dsolve( diff(y(x),x,x) + y(x)^3/(1+x), y(x) );

kilobytes used=25135, alloc=18748, time=2.72
Out[18]:
$$y \left(x \right) = \left(\frac{\textit{\_a}}{\sqrt{-{\mathrm e}^{-2 \left(\int \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)d \textit{\_a} \right)-2 c_{1}}}}\right)\boldsymbol{\mathrm{where}}\left[\left\{\frac{d}{d \textit{\_a}}\textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)=\left(4 \textit{\_a}^{3}+3 \textit{\_a} \right) \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)^{3}+4 \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)^{2}\right\}, \left\{\textit{\_a} =y \left(x \right) \sqrt{1+x}, \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)=\frac{\sqrt{1+x}}{\left(-1-x \right) \left(2 \left(\frac{d}{d x}y \left(x \right)\right) x +2 \frac{d}{d x}y \left(x \right)+y \left(x \right)\right)}\right\}, \left\{x =-{\mathrm e}^{-2 \left(\int \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)d \textit{\_a} \right)-2 c_{1}}-1, y \left(x \right)=\frac{\textit{\_a}}{\sqrt{-{\mathrm e}^{-2 \left(\int \textit{\_}b\left(\textit{\_a} \right)d \textit{\_a} \right)-2 c_{1}}}}\right\}\right]$$

Use of special functions¶

Maple's knowledge of special functions and linear second order differential equations is extremely strong. So for most equations like the following, Maple will readily give a solution. But you might have to look up what the answer means!

In [19]:
LinearODE := diff( y(t), t, t) + (1+t)*diff(y(t),t) + t*y(t);
Out[19]:
$$\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}y \left(t \right)+\left(1+t \right) \left(\frac{d}{d t}y \left(t \right)\right)+t y \left(t \right)$$
In [20]:
dsolve( LinearODE, y(t) );
Out[20]:
$$y \left(t \right) = c_{1} {\mathrm e}^{-t}+c_{2} {\mathrm e}^{-t} \mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2} \left(-1+t \right)}{2}\right)$$

"erf" is the "error function". You can find help on that The Maple Help pages

If you want official instruction on special functions you can go to the Digital Library of Mathematical Functions

or to Fredrik Johansson's The Function Grimoire

Or you can use the FunctionAdvisor in Maple itself (not yet in the Jupyter Notebook interface).

Boundary conditions¶

The easiest kind of problem to solve has it's conditions specified at only one point---"initial conditions" also called the Cauchy specification.

But frequently in practice we know things or want things about the solution to happen at different places. Most commonly, just two: the beginning and the end.

In [21]:
BoundaryConditions := {y(-3)=1, y(2)=-1};
Out[21]:
$$\{y \left(-3\right) = 1, y \left(2\right) = -1\}$$
In [22]:
soln := dsolve( {LinearODE} union BoundaryConditions, y(t) );
Out[22]:
$$y \left(t \right) = \frac{{\mathrm e}^{-3-t} \left(-\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2} \left(-1+t \right)}{2}\right) {\mathrm e}^{5}-{\mathrm e}^{5} \mathrm{erf}\left(2 \sqrt{2}\right)-\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2} \left(-1+t \right)}{2}\right)+\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)\right)}{\mathrm{erf}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)+\mathrm{erf}\left(2 \sqrt{2}\right)}$$
In [23]:
plot( rhs( soln ), t=-3..2, thickness=2, color="Executive Blue", 
 gridlines, view=[-3..2, -2..2]);
Out[23]:

Sometimes Maple can solve the differential equation but cannot identify the arbitrary constants that come up because the boundary conditions give nonlinear algebraic equations to solve. Sometimes the solutions don't exist or sometimes there are infinitely many solutions (this is called an eigenvalue problem).

In [24]:
dsolve( {diff(y(t),t,t) + (2*n+1)^2*y(t) = 0, y(-Pi/2)=0, y(Pi/2)=0 }, y(t) ) 
   assuming n::integer ;
Out[24]:
$$y \left(t \right) = c_{2} \cos \left(\left(2 n +1\right) t \right)$$

Maple can give answers that are different on different intervals using its "piecewise" function.

In [25]:
psol := dsolve( {diff(y(t),t,t) + y(t) = abs(t), y(-Pi)=0, y(Pi)=0}, y(t) )
Out[25]:
$$y \left(t \right) = \sin \left(t \right) c_{2} +\cos \left(t \right) \pi -\left(\left\{\begin{array}{cc} t & t \le 0 \\ -t +2 \sin \left(t \right) & 0<t \end{array}\right.\right)$$
In [26]:
plot( diff(eval(rhs(psol), c__2=0),t,t,t), t=-Pi..Pi, discont=true );
Out[26]:

Piecewise functions occur naturally as input, also.

In [27]:
psol := dsolve( {diff(y(t),t,t) = piecewise(t<0, sin(t), cos(t)/(1+t)), 
         y(-Pi)=0, D(y)(-Pi)=0}, y(t) );

kilobytes used=72004, alloc=24074, time=6.69
Out[27]:
$$y \left(t \right) = -\pi -\sin \left(t \right)-\left(\left\{\begin{array}{cc} t & t <0 \\ -\cos \left(1\right) \left(1+t \right) \mathrm{Ci}\left(1+t \right)-\sin \left(1\right) \left(1+t \right) \mathrm{Si}\left(1+t \right)+ \\ \mathrm{Ci}\left(1\right) \left(1+t \right) \cos \left(1\right)+\left(1+t \right) \mathrm{Si}\left(1\right) \sin \left(1\right)+2 t & 0\le t \end{array}\right.\right)$$

That answer contains "Sine integrals" and "Cosine integrals" Si and Ci. You can look them up, but they are defined by integrals.

In [28]:
diff( Ci(t), t );
Out[28]:
$$\frac{\cos \left(t \right)}{t}$$
In [29]:
Ci(0);

Runtime error: Error, (in Ci) numeric exception: division by zero
In [30]:
series( Ci(t), t );
Out[30]:
$$\gamma +\ln \left(t \right)-\frac{1}{4} t^{2}+\frac{1}{96} t^{4}+\mathrm{O}\left(t^{6}\right)$$
In [31]:
plot( eval(y(t), psol), t=-Pi..Pi );
Out[31]:

That solution involves Airy functions (which are quite interesting---Sir George Biddell Airy was an astronomer, and he needed these functions to explain the rainbow).

In [40]:

So the solution is singular for some t between about -1.5 and -1.4.

In [41]:
fsolve(den, t=-2..-1);
Out[41]:
$$- 1.436348184$$

This explains the radius of convergence of the series solution.

dsolve( diff(y(x),x,x) = x*y(x), y(x) );
Out[42]:
$$y \left(x \right) = c_{1} \mathit{Ai}\left(x \right)+c_{2} \mathit{Bi}\left(x \right)$$

Solving differential equations numerically is extremely important, versatile, and reliable. Maple has excellent facilities for this (comparable to Matlab's and to Python's; the features of Julia are pretty much state-of-the-art these days).

In [46]:
wavyde := diff(y(x),x) - cos(Pi*x*y(x));
Out[46]:
$$\frac{d}{d x}y \left(x \right)-\cos \left(\pi x y \left(x \right)\right)$$
In [47]:
dsolve( wavyde, y(x) ); # No analytic solution known, no answer given

kilobytes used=108716, alloc=24074, time=10.58
In [48]:
N := 100: # Solve for N different initial conditions
sols := Array(1..N):
plts := Array(1..N):
for k to N do
  ic := 6.0*k/N;
  sols[k] := dsolve( {wavyde, y(0)=ic}, y(x), numeric, range=0..6,
                     abserr=1.0e-11 ); # Choose a tight tolerance
  plts[k] := plots[odeplot](sols[k], [x,y(x)] );
end do:
plots[display]( seq(plts[k],k=1..N), gridlines );
Out[48]:

A Warning. Sometimes Maple is not correct.¶

The following differential equation is apparently solved in Maple. But there is a hidden difficulty.

In [49]:
nastyde := diff(y(x),x) = x^2*(x^2-y(x)^2);
Out[49]:
$$\frac{d}{d x}y \left(x \right) = x^{2} \left(x^{2}-y \left(x \right)^{2}\right)$$
In [50]:
subtlywrong := dsolve( {nastyde, y(-1)=0}, y(x) );

kilobytes used=124658, alloc=24623, time=12.55
Out[50]:
$$y \left(x \right) = -\frac{x \left(I_{-\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right) K_{\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)-K_{\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right) I_{-\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)\right)}{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) I_{-\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) K_{\frac{5}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}$$

Those "I"s and "K"s are Bessel functions, which are very important in a number of branches of physics and engineering.

The problem is that the differential equation has a "turning point" at $x=0$ and this breaks algebra. The constant of integration has to change at that point!

In [51]:
testplot := plot( eval(y(x), subtlywrong), x=-1..2, discont=true, 
      color=red, gridlines, view=[-1..2,-1..2]  );
Out[51]:
In [52]:
fixit := dsolve( nastyde, y(x) );
Out[52]:
$$y \left(x \right) = -\frac{x c_{1} K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)}{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) c_{1} +I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)}+\frac{I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) x^{4}+3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) c_{1} +3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)}{x^{3} \left(K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) c_{1} +I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)\right)}$$
In [53]:
lefteq := eval( eval( y(x), fixit ), x=-1 ) = 0;
Out[53]:
$$\frac{c_{1} K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right) c_{1} +I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}-\frac{I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right) c_{1} +3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right) c_{1} +I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)} = 0$$
In [54]:

Out[54]:
$$\frac{3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}{-3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}$$
In [55]:
leftside := eval(rhs(fixit), c__1=leftc1 );
Out[55]:
$$-\frac{x \left(3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\right) K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)}{\left(-3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\right) \left(\frac{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) \left(3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\right)}{-3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}+I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)\right)}+\frac{I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) x^{4}+\frac{3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) \left(3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\right)}{-3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}+3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)}{x^{3} \left(\frac{K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right) \left(3 I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+I_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)\right)}{-3 K_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)+K_{\frac{11}{8}}\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)}+I_{\frac{3}{8}}\left(\frac{x^{4}}{4}\right)\right)}$$

There's a lot more to be said about differential equations in Maple. One can use Maple to vary parameters and see what happens. One can build applets with sliders to do so. One can examine differential equations that do not satisfy Lipschitz conditions and have more than one solution. One can solve problems with "moveable poles." One can solve problems approximately using perturbation methods (I am currently writing a book with Nic Fillion on just that, and wow do I ever want to tell you more about that, but your professor says that should wait till "next year" :).

Remember: always plot your solutions.¶

When you use Maple, or any computer algebra system, be careful, and don't expect too much. But a lot of work by a lot of people has gone into the systems over the years (decades!) and they can be very useful indeed.
